            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "This happens because `nvim_open_win` copies options from the current window into the new floating window. MatchParen uses a `WinLeave` autocommand to clear highlights in the non-active window. When the float is created, it copies everything from the current window (including MatchParen highlights), but a `WinLeave` autocommand is never triggered, so the highlight is never cleared.\r\n\r\nI see the same thing with `'cursorline'` (I have a `WinLeave` autocommand to clear `'cursorline'` in non-active windows).\r\n\r\nWe don't see this with e.g. `:new` or `:split` because when a split is created, the new window is entered, which triggers a `WinLeave` event on the original window.\r\n\r\nI'm not sure what the best solution is. Firing a `WinLeave` event after creating a float doesn't seem semantically correct, since the float was never entered in the first place. ",
